## What to do
Create an Express error-handling middleware that catches all unhandled errors and returns safe responses.

### Error handler behavior
```typescript
export function errorHandler(): ErrorRequestHandler {
  return (err, req, res, next) => {
    // 1. Log the full error (stack trace, details) via pino logger
    // 2. In production (NODE_ENV=production):
    //    - Return { error: 'Internal Server Error' } with status 500
    //    - Never include stack traces, file paths, or internal details
    //    - For known error types (ValidationError, RateLimitError), return appropriate status codes
    // 3. In development:
    //    - Return { error: err.message, stack: err.stack } for debugging
  }
}
```

### Known error types to handle
- ValidationError (400) — missing/invalid request params
- RateLimitError (429) — rate limit exceeded (include Retry-After header)
- AuthenticationError (401) — invalid OTP, expired session
- ForbiddenError (403) — invalid HMAC signature
- NotFoundError (404) — unknown route
- All others (500) — generic internal error

### Custom error classes
Create simple error classes:
```typescript
export class AppError extends Error {
  constructor(message: string, public statusCode: number, public isOperational: boolean = true) {
    super(message)
  }
}
export class ValidationError extends AppError { constructor(msg: string) { super(msg, 400) } }
export class RateLimitError extends AppError { constructor(retryAfter: number) { super('Too Many Requests', 429); this.retryAfter = retryAfter } }
export class AuthenticationError extends AppError { constructor(msg: string) { super(msg, 401) } }
```

## Don't
- Expose stack traces in production
- Expose file paths in production
- Expose database error details in production
- Swallow errors without logging them
- Use console.log (use pino logger)

